<DocsLayout
  title="MCP integration"
  eyebrow="Capabilities"
  description="Attaching Model Context Protocol servers to a session."
  prev={{ href: "/docs/tools/", title: "Built-in tools" }}
  next={{ href: "/docs/goal-mode/", title: "Goal mode" }}
>
  <p>
    gode is an MCP host. You can attach <strong>stdio MCP servers</strong> per session, and
    the tools they expose are folded into gode's tool registry under
    <code>mcp.&lt;server-name&gt;.&lt;tool-name&gt;</code>. From the model's perspective they
    are just more tools.
  </p>

  <h2>Attaching servers via ACP</h2>
  <p>
    On <code>session/new</code>, pass <code>mcpServers</code>. <code>command</code> must be
    an absolute path:
  </p>
  <pre><code>{`{"jsonrpc":"2.0","id":2,"method":"session/new","params":{
  "cwd":"/absolute/path/to/workspace",
  "mcpServers":[{
    "name":"tools",
    "command":"/absolute/path/to/mcp-server",
    "args":["--stdio"],
    "env":[{"name":"EXAMPLE","value":"1"}]
  }]
}}`}</code></pre>

  <h2>Lifecycle</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>The MCP manager spawns the server process when the session starts.</li>
    <li>It performs the MCP handshake and registers all returned tools.</li>
    <li>Tool calls are routed back to the server over the same stdio transport.</li>
    <li>When the session closes, the server process is terminated cleanly.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Transport coverage</h2>
  <p>
    gode currently advertises <strong>stdio</strong> MCP servers only. HTTP and SSE
    transports are not advertised yet — clients should not assume them.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Why isolate tools as MCP servers?</strong> Process isolation, language
    independence, and independent shipping. Built-in tools win on integration depth; MCP
    tools win on portability and blast radius.
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
